##############################################

Context("LimitedFraction");
Context()->flags->set(requirePureFractions=>0);
Context()->flags->set(showMixedNumbers=>1);

$int1 = random(2,5,1);
$num1 = 0;
$den1 = 1;
$frac1 = Fraction($num1,$den1);

$int2 = 0;
$num2 = random(1,5,1);
do {$den2 = random($num2+1,10,1);} until (gcd($num2,$den2)==1);
$frac2 = Fraction($num2,$den2);

$ans = $int1 + $int2 + $frac1 - $frac2->reduce;

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Add the following: [`` (-[$frac2]) + [$int1] ``]

    [___________]{$ans} 

END_PGML

##############################################

$absInt1 = abs($int1);
$absAns = abs($ans);
$s1 = -1*$num2+$int1*$den2;

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

##Method 1  

When we add a positive number and a negative number, we need to find the difference of their absolute values. In other words, to do [` [$frac2] + ([$int1]) `], first we do [` [$absInt1] - [$frac2] `].

We can "split" [`1`] from the integer, and do [` 1 - [$frac2] `]:

    [``
\begin{aligned}[t]
   [$absInt1] - [$frac2] 
      &= [$absInt1-1] + 1 - [$frac2] \\
      &= [$absInt1-1] + \frac{[$den2]}{[$den2]} - [$frac2] \\
      &= [$absInt1-1] + \frac{[$den2]-[$num2]}{[$den2]} \\
      &= [$absInt1-1] + \frac{[$den2-$num2]}{[$den2]} \\
      &= [$absAns]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

Note that we changed [`1`] to [`\frac{[$den2]}{[$den2]}`].

Finally, since the absolute value of the positive number, [`[$int1]`], is bigger than that of the negative number, [`[$frac2]`], the answer is positive.

[` (-[$frac2]) + [$int1] = [$ans] `]

##Method2  

We could simply change the integer [`[$int1]`] into a fraction without "splitting":

    [``
\begin{aligned}[t]
   (-[$frac2]) + [$int1] 
      &= (-[$frac2]) + \frac{[$int1]}{1} \\
      &= (-[$frac2]) + \frac{[$int1] \cdot [$den2]}{1 \cdot [$den2]} \\
      &= (-[$frac2]) + \frac{[$int1*$den2]}{[$den2]} \\
      &= \frac{-[$num2]+[$int1*$den2]}{[$den2]} \\
      &= \frac{[$s1]}{[$den2]} \\
      &= [$ans]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

